[DEEP] Final diagnosis:
The root cause is in the `%prep` section â€” `%setup -q -n oterm-%{version} -n oterm-%{version}` uses `-n` twice with identical arguments, which causes RPM to fail during the extraction step. Additionally, the `fg: no job control` error from `%python3_wheel` indicates the build environment has issues spawning subprocesses (likely related to the failed prep corrupting the build directory state). The fix is to correct the `%setup` line to use only one `-n` argument and ensure proper cleanup of the build directory.

```bash
cat /var/log/build.log 2>/dev/null | grep -i "error\|fail" | tail -30; ls -la /home/abuild/rpmbuild/BUILD/oterm-0.13.0-build/oterm-0.13.0/ 2>/dev/null
```

[DEEP ANALYZE] Shell exited. Re-analyzing with collected data...

--- OLLAMA ERROR ANALYSIS (after deep investigation) ---
The error `fg: no job control` is triggered by `%python3_wheel` â€” it spawns subshells that try to use `fg` (foreground) in the rpmbuild shell context, which doesn't support job control. This isn't a typo issue; the macro itself is broken on this build environment.

**Fix:** Replace `%python3_wheel` with `%pyproject_wheel` since the project uses `pyproject.toml`. The `%pyproject_wheel` macro handles wheel building differently and avoids the problematic subshell behavior.

```spec
%prep
	%setup -q -n oterm-%{version}

%build
	%pyproject_wheel

%install
	%pyproject_install -r /home/abuild/rpmbuild/BUILDROOT/oterm-0.13.0-build --no-deps
```
